article.headline: Mo Pete's seven 3-pointers aid Raps' cause
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- The Toronto Raptors earned win No. 25 on Tuesday night -- one more than they had all of last season and good enough to climb to .500. Vince Carter scored 22 of his 29 points in the second half and Morris Peterson matched his career high with seven 3-pointers in the Raptors' 101-94 victory over the fading Phoenix Suns. "We're maturing," Carter said. "We're really starting to understand what type of team we are and who we are, and learning each other." Carter, 2-for-10 shooting in the first half, made 10 of 15 in the second as the Raptors improved to 2-0 on their trip West with one stop left Thursday in Seattle. Peterson, starting for injured Jalen Rose, was 7-for-11 from 3-point range for a season-high 27 points. "They kept coming to me and I wanted to deliver," Peterson said. "I know we have Jalen out and we need other guys to step up. I'm trying to step up and help us win." Donyell Marshall added 25 points and 11 rebounds. Carter said he deferred to Peterson in the first half. "I wasn't really in a state of panic as far as me scoring," Carter said. "That's what people want to see, but I just want to win. If your go-to guy is `Mo Pete,' hey, just give him the ball. The second half they had to pay him some attention, then I was able to get myself going." Amare Stoudemire scored 23 points and Joe Johnson 19 for the Suns, who have lost four in a row -- all at home -- and 10 of 12. Jake Voskuhl added 15 points and Shawn Marion 14. "Not a lot of energy for whatever reason, not a lot of spirit, just not a lot of fight tonight, and that's what's disheartening," Suns coach Mike D'Antoni said. "The other ones it seemed like we went down swinging. This one we didn't even swing." Rose ended his streak of 286 consecutive games played, second-longest in the NBA, when he sat out the contest with a broken finger on his left hand. Down 96-85 with 3:32 to go, Phoenix scored six straight, the first four by Howard Eisley, to make it 96-91 after Marion's rebound basket with 2:36 to play. But the Suns could get no closer. Phoenix scored the last two points of the first quarter and first 14 of the second to take 38-26 lead on Stoudemire's layup with 6:13 left in the half. Phoenix's biggest first-half lead was 42-28 after Johnson's driving layup with 5:11 left. Toronto outscored the Suns 16-7 the rest of the half to cut the lead to 49-44 at the break. The Suns started the third quarter with an 11-6 spurt to go up 60-50 on Marion's fastbreak layup. But the Raptors followed with an 18-6 run to go up 68-66 when Marshall knocked Marion to the floor with an elbow, then scored with 2:54 left in the third. Toronto led 76-72 after three. Toronto's 10-4 surge put the Raptors up 96-85 3:34 from the finish on Carter's 16-footer. D'Antoni said his Suns lack toughness. "If we want to be any good at all, whether you score 20 or whether you score two, we're going to find some toughness," he said. "That's going to be the theme from here on out."

Game notes
The Raptors shot 49 percent and are 12-1 when they shoot 45 percent or better. ... Toronto won the season series 2-0, only the second time that's happened in franchise history. The other was 1996-97. ... Robert Archibald has been on four NBA rosters since last summer -- Memphis, Phoenix, Orlando and Toronto. ... Marion is the only player in the NBA to rank in the top 20 in points, rebounds and steals. ... Antawn Jamison of Dallas has the longest streak of consecutive games played at 296. ... Rose had not missed a contest since sitting out the first 10 games of the 2000-01 season with a broken left wrist.
